  "Allegations" : "FINRA RULE 2010, NASD RULE 3030: JAN ATTEMPTED TO ARRANGE AN OUTSIDE THIRD-PARTY BUSINESS LOAN FOR A PROSPECTIVE CLIENT WITHOUT OBTAINING WRITTEN AUTHORIZATION OR OTHERWISE NOTIFYING HIS MEMBER FIRM. IF SUCCESSFUL, JAN WOULD RECEIVE A REFERRAL FEE. THE POTENTIAL CLIENT AGREED AND JAN, USING HIS PERSONAL EMAIL ACCOUNT ON HIS HOME COMPUTER, SENT THE PROSPECTIVE CLIENT A DETAILED CLIENT INFORMATION SHEET FROM AN OUTSIDE LENDER. THE DOCUMENT JAN SENT REQUIRED THE PROSPECTIVE CLIENT TO PROVIDE 31 SEPARATE PIECES OF INFORMATION RELATING TO THE POTENTIAL LOAN, INCLUDING A PASSPORT NUMBER, BUSINESS TAX ID NUMBER, AND BANK ACCOUNT INFORMATION. JAN ALSO REQUESTED A COPY OF THE POTENTIAL CLIENT'S PASSPORT AND A COPY OF A BANK GUARANTEE OR STANDBY LETTER OF CREDIT \"FOR OUR REVIEW AND ACCEPTANCE.\" ALTHOUGH JAN USED HIS PERSONAL EMAIL ACCOUNT, HIS SIGNATURE BLOCK IDENTIFIED HIM AS A \"FINANCIAL CONSULTANT\" WITH HIS FIRM. JAN NEVER PROVIDED WRITTEN NOTICE TO HIS FIRM OF HIS INTENT TO, NOR THE FACT THAT HE ENGAGED IN EFFORTS TO OBTAIN A THIRD-PARTY LOAN FOR THE PROSPECTIVE CLIENT. JAN THEREBY ENGAGED IN BUSINESS OUTSIDE THE SCOPE OF HIS RELATIONSHIP WITH HIS FIRM WITHOUT PROVIDING PROMPT WRITTEN NOTICE TO HIS FIRM. JAN'S CONDUCT WAS ALSO CONTRARY TO HIS FIRM'S WRITTEN POLICIES AND PROCEDURES. IN ADDITION TO CONDUCTING OUTSIDE BUSINESS WITH A PROSPECTIVE CLIENT THROUGH JAN'S PERSONAL EMAIL ACCOUNT, JAN ALSO ADMITTED ATTEMPTING TO SOLICIT BUSINESS FROM AN UNSPECIFIED NUMBER OF OTHER CUSTOMERS USING HIS PERSONAL EMAIL ACCOUNT. FURTHER, AT TIMES, JAN COMMUNICATED WITH ONE FIRM CUSTOMER, WHO HAD TWO FIRM ACCOUNTS, THROUGH JAN'S HOME EMAIL ACCOUNT ABOUT DETAILS RELATING TO AN ASSET THAT WAS TO BE DEPOSITED IN ONE OF THE CUSTOMER'S ACCOUNTS. JAN KNEW THAT HIS FIRM'S PROCEDURES REQUIRED APPROVAL OF HIS EMAIL. JAN THEREBY CIRCUMVENTED HIS FIRM'S SUPERVISORY PROCEDURES AND COMPROMISED THE FIRM'S ABILITY TO SUPERVISE AND MONITOR HIS COMMUNICATIONS WITH THE PUBLIC.",
